<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="27" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="27">
<taxonomicName authority="subsp. trivialis" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Poa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Poa trivialis subsp. trivialis" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="trivialis" subSpecies="trivialis">Poa trivialis subsp. trivialis</taxonomicName>
is reputedly self-incompatible and sexually reproducing (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1979.10432571" author="Connor, HE" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Journal of Botany" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" pagination="547 - 574" refId="B7" refString="Connor, HE, 1979. Breeding systems in the grasses: A survey. New Zealand Journal of Botany 17 (4): 547 - 574, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1979.10432571" title="Breeding systems in the grasses: A survey." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/0028825X.1979.10432571" volume="17" year="1979">Connor 1979</bibRefCitation>
). It can be quite invasive in temperate climates with a cool wet season. Aesthetically, it makes a poor lawn grass due to its sprawling habit when mown. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Valdés">Valdes</normalizedToken>
and Scholz (2009) recorded it only for Algeria in North Africa. The second major subspecies, 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="P. t. subsp. sylvicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="subSpecies" species="t." subSpecies="sylvicola">P. t. subsp. sylvicola</taxonomicName>
(Guss.) H. Lindb., has bead-like swellings along the stolons and more hair on the lemma marginal veins and is more tolerant of drought: It is infrequently found outside of the Mediterranean basin and Irano-Turainian floristic region, but is reported across northern Africa (
<bibRefCitation author="Valdes, B" journalOrPublisher="Annals of the Missouri Botanical Garden" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" publicationUrl="http://www.emplantbase.org/home.html" refId="B28" refString="Valdes, B, Scholz, H, Raab-Straube von, E, Parolly, G, 2009. Poaceae (pro parte majore). Euro+Med Plantbase - the information resource for Euro-Mediterranean plant diversity. http://www.emplantbase.org/home.html" title="Poaceae (pro parte majore). Euro + Med Plantbase - the information resource for Euro-Mediterranean plant diversity." url="http://www.emplantbase.org/home.html" year="2009">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Valdés">Valdes</normalizedToken>
and Scholz 2009
</bibRefCitation>
). 2 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">n</emphasis>
= 
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">14</emphasis>
, 14 + 1 - 2B, 15, 27, 28 (27 and 28 counts not confirmed to subspecies may represent subsp. 
<taxonomicName genus="P." lsidName="subsp. sylvicola" pageId="0" pageNumber="27" rank="subSpecies" species="t." subSpecies="sylvicola">sylvicola</taxonomicName>
). - 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="27">Vv</emphasis>
genotype.
</paragraph>
